{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2010"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2010"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.26,0.54,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2010"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42346"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2010"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2010"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1015"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"787"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/42346"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old male presents to the nephrology clinic with his father with a history of recurrent haematuria, and hearing impairment. The patient\u2019s medical history is unremarkable with no hypertension or diabetes. Further history revealed a maternal grandfather who had hearing loss and passed away from renal failure. Physical examination reveals bilateral sensorineural hearing loss, and laboratory investigations confirm the presence of microscopic haematuria and proteinuria. Renal function tests indicate mildly elevated serum creatinine levels. A renal biopsy is performed, and histopathological examination reveals thinning and splitting of the glomerular basement membrane. Genetic testing is conducted and the patient and his family are counselled about the genetic nature of the condition and the potential for progression to renal failure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most common pattern of inheritance for the likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autosomal dominant","Autosomal recessive","X-linked inheritance","Non-Mendelian inheritance","De novo mutation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBased on the clinical scenario describing a child with kidney disease, sensorineural hearing loss, visual abnormalities, and histopathological findings of renal biopsy, the most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EAlport syndrome.\u003C/strong\u003E It is caused by mutations in genes responsible for type IV collagen production in the basement membrane of the kidneys and other organs. Roughly two thirds of cases of Alport syndrome are inherited in an \u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked manner\u003C/strong\u003E, and approximately 20% is autosomal dominant, and approximately 15% is autosomal recessive. Common features include haematuria, proteinuria, and sensorineural hearing loss. In some cases, eye issues such as lens abnormalities may occur. The condition often progresses to kidney failure, emphasizing the need for early detection and management. Genetic testing and renal biopsy are key for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Alport syndrome is inherited in an X-linked manner","The classical triad seen in Alport syndrome is kidney disease, sensorineural hearing loss, and visual abnormalities"],"references":["Kashtan CE. Alport Syndrome. 2001 Aug 28 [Updated 2019 Feb 21]. In: Adam MP, Feldman J, Mirzaa GM, et al., editors. GeneReviews\u00ae [Internet]. Seattle (WA): University of Washington, Seattle; 1993-2024. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK1207/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2010"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"27367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/27367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-02-07T20:42:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T09:43:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2010"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"42346"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the